WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.140
So, this is a talk about the sort of other end of the spectrum of turning 45-second tasks

00:00:11.140 --> 00:00:14.920
into 5-second tasks with LLMs.

00:00:14.920 --> 00:00:20.280
If you're the sort of person who in the past has been frustrated by this process of steering

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:26.360
LLMs and correcting their errors, this might be the time to revisit and explore what it

00:00:26.360 --> 00:00:35.320
feels like for LLMs to be very good at small, specific tasks.

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:41.080
So for an example, let's imagine we're writing this function in R. It's a silly little wrapper

00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:43.500
around sys.getenv.

00:00:43.500 --> 00:00:49.599
So we're grabbing the value of an environmental variable, and if that environmental variable

00:00:49.599 --> 00:00:56.919
isn't set, we're raising an error that says I can't find that environmental variable.

00:00:56.919 --> 00:00:58.959
So Matthew queued this up really nicely.

00:00:58.959 --> 00:01:00.560
What do we not like to do?

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:03.200
Write documentation.

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:07.720
In my gig as an R developer day-to-day, writing documentation is something that I do all the

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:09.559
time.

00:01:09.559 --> 00:01:13.720
There are many parts of writing documentation that I think are pretty interesting, like

00:01:13.720 --> 00:01:18.279
eliciting the connections between different functions in my packages and the packages

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:20.160
that I'm interfacing with.

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:28.320
But there's a lot of parts of it that are pretty boring, like templating out boilerplate.

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:37.839
So for example of what this function does, the home variable is Simon Couch on my computer,

00:01:37.839 --> 00:01:40.559
but the variable I'm a silly goose doesn't exist.

00:01:40.559 --> 00:01:47.320
So this function would raise an error in that case.

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:52.639
So today I'm going to be introducing the chores package, which is a package that helps you

00:01:52.639 --> 00:01:58.000
automate hard-to-automate sort of fuzzy tasks using a markdown file.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:03.879
So in this example, I have this key get function, and I need to write or start writing Roxygen

00:02:03.879 --> 00:02:06.040
documentation.

00:02:06.040 --> 00:02:12.360
So in this video, I will highlight the function, I'll press a key command to pull up a small

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:20.039
shiny applet, I'll select the Roxygen helper from inside that applet, and a template of

00:02:20.039 --> 00:02:23.919
the documentation will begin streaming in.

00:02:23.919 --> 00:02:28.279
So something like this already exists inside of RStudio and will be coming soon to Positron,

00:02:28.279 --> 00:02:31.479
which is like the insert Roxygen skeleton.

00:02:31.479 --> 00:02:35.880
And so that will give you like at param name, at param error call.

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:41.600
We can get a little further along the way using the chores package, because the LLM

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:49.320
can actually infer the sorts of formats of the arguments to that function.

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:55.240
So this prompt is sort of tuned to give me the least amount of documentation possible

00:02:55.240 --> 00:02:59.800
while being thorough enough to where I don't want to delete anything.

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:05.559
I don't want to read through a bunch of stuff that's not exactly how I would write it.

00:03:05.559 --> 00:03:10.800
This isn't complete documentation, but it's just complete enough to where all of this

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:14.320
seems reasonable and I don't want to delete any of it.

00:03:14.320 --> 00:03:19.160
Or not reading through slop, if you will.

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:21.639
So this is a talk about the chores package.

00:03:21.639 --> 00:03:28.279
The chores package is intended to help you with repetitive, hard to automate tasks.

00:03:28.279 --> 00:03:33.000
They're sort of like smart RStudio snippets.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:41.600
I know this is the cutest hex sticker you will see at this conference, unfortunately.

00:03:41.600 --> 00:03:45.039
Unfortunately I don't have any with me, but maybe you can track me down at conf if you'll

00:03:45.039 --> 00:03:48.240
be there.

00:03:48.240 --> 00:03:51.160
So let's talk a little bit about how chores works.

00:03:51.160 --> 00:03:55.160
If you were tracking along with Hadley's keynote yesterday, you might actually find this somewhat

00:03:55.160 --> 00:03:57.279
intuitive.

00:03:57.279 --> 00:04:01.860
So the first thing that you do as a user is you make a code selection.

00:04:01.860 --> 00:04:07.380
So in our example, I selected the full body of that key get function.

00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:11.100
And then I trigger an add-in and select a helper.

00:04:11.100 --> 00:04:17.500
So I highlight the function, and then once you've installed the chores package, you will

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:21.619
have an RStudio add-in available to you.

00:04:21.619 --> 00:04:26.420
And that add-in can be configured to any key command.

00:04:26.420 --> 00:04:29.540
Unfortunately it's kind of naughty for me to just do that for you as much as I wish

00:04:29.540 --> 00:04:34.220
I could as a developer.

00:04:34.220 --> 00:04:37.480
And so once I press that key command, I have a small applet.

00:04:37.480 --> 00:04:43.739
You can see there are three default selections in the chores package called test that, Roxygen,

00:04:43.739 --> 00:04:45.100
and CLI.

00:04:45.100 --> 00:04:50.140
These are references to three different tasks that I do almost every day in developing R

00:04:50.140 --> 00:04:53.179
packages.

00:04:53.179 --> 00:04:58.179
But you can add a helper to this list by just creating a markdown file.

00:04:58.179 --> 00:05:05.140
And I'll talk a little bit more about how you can do that here in a sec.

00:05:05.140 --> 00:05:09.500
And so the next thing, each of these helpers corresponds to a system prompt.

00:05:09.500 --> 00:05:13.260
So I had they introduced yesterday this idea of a system prompt where you can steer the

00:05:13.260 --> 00:05:17.579
behavior of a model to do something specific.

00:05:17.579 --> 00:05:21.059
So in this example, I'm saying you're a tourist assistant.

00:05:21.059 --> 00:05:23.540
I'm going to show you some function code.

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:29.700
Just respond with Roxygen documentation and then blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

00:05:29.700 --> 00:05:34.619
The nice part about working with chores is that once you've typed this out, interacting

00:05:34.619 --> 00:05:36.859
with the package isn't like a chat at all.

00:05:36.859 --> 00:05:46.500
You're literally pressing a key command and your interaction with the LLM is done.

00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:50.859
Then that prompt in the selection you've made inside of your code editor is sent to the

00:05:50.859 --> 00:05:51.859
LLM.

00:05:51.859 --> 00:05:55.619
So if you're an Elmer user, it looks sort of like this.

00:05:55.619 --> 00:05:57.859
You initiate a chat object.

00:05:57.859 --> 00:06:02.540
The chores package is compatible with any model that's compatible with Elmer.

00:06:02.540 --> 00:06:07.899
So that could be Anthropx Cloud, OpenAI, Chat2BT, so on.

00:06:07.899 --> 00:06:14.619
And then the code that you select inside of your editor is sent to the model.

00:06:14.619 --> 00:06:20.540
The model responds with, in this case, some Roxygen documentation.

00:06:20.540 --> 00:06:26.179
And that response is inlined directly into your source editor.

00:06:26.179 --> 00:06:33.179
And finally, that response is written to the editor using the RStudio API.

00:06:33.179 --> 00:06:37.940
So the interesting thing about this particular part of how this package works is that this

00:06:37.940 --> 00:06:40.019
is all happening in R code.

00:06:40.019 --> 00:06:43.399
So if you're an RStudio user, this works in RStudio.

00:06:43.399 --> 00:06:47.100
If you're a Positron user, this works inside of there.

00:06:47.100 --> 00:06:52.019
There's an implementation of the RStudio API that several other IDEs have made.

00:06:52.019 --> 00:06:55.299
And so if you're interested in whether this package works there, you can just try it,

00:06:55.299 --> 00:06:59.880
and it might.

00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:05.220
So I called out that this package supports a couple things that I do every day as a package

00:07:05.220 --> 00:07:06.299
developer.

00:07:06.299 --> 00:07:12.299
But any repetitive task that you do in your day-to-day work in your IDE, if you can describe

00:07:12.299 --> 00:07:19.299
it in a markdown file and the sufficient context for resolving that request is just

00:07:19.299 --> 00:07:24.420
selecting some code, then you can make that happen with chores.

00:07:24.420 --> 00:07:28.260
So the first one that I showed you was templating out Roxygen documentation.

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:31.739
You can also transition erroring code to use the CLI package.

00:07:31.739 --> 00:07:38.820
So if I have a call to stop or message or warn, sprint F, take your pick, any of those

00:07:38.940 --> 00:07:43.779
can be converted to this more modern interface that the Tidyverse team has been transitioning

00:07:43.779 --> 00:07:44.779
to.

00:07:44.779 --> 00:07:47.019
And the same goes for test that code.

00:07:47.019 --> 00:07:52.859
So a few years ago, the third edition of test that was released, and it's so painful to

00:07:52.859 --> 00:07:54.459
convert packages over to it.

00:07:54.459 --> 00:08:00.019
We're really happy to have this as a resource now.

00:08:00.019 --> 00:08:04.619
So again, if you can describe this coding task that you do all the time in a markdown

00:08:04.619 --> 00:08:11.100
file and all you need as additional context to say, this is the specific task that you're

00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:17.899
working on this time, if that can be encapsulated in a code selection, then you can use it in

00:08:17.899 --> 00:08:21.859
a chore.

00:08:21.859 --> 00:08:25.579
This is the part of the talk where I tell you that you have to put your credit card

00:08:25.579 --> 00:08:31.100
information down to use my R package, which is like the lamest part of starting to work

00:08:31.100 --> 00:08:34.419
on language models now.

00:08:34.419 --> 00:08:36.340
But hopefully soon, this won't be the case.

00:08:36.340 --> 00:08:40.260
I'll talk a little bit right now about what the landscape looks like.

00:08:40.260 --> 00:08:44.539
Once you download the chores package, you will have to make the decision of what model

00:08:44.539 --> 00:08:48.260
you want to use to power it.

00:08:48.260 --> 00:08:54.440
Okay, familiar territory, we're on the XY plane.

00:08:54.440 --> 00:08:59.979
On the X axis, we have the price per 100 refactorings.

00:08:59.979 --> 00:09:04.859
So if I generate Roxygen documentation 100 times, this is the price that we're looking

00:09:04.859 --> 00:09:06.859
at.

00:09:06.859 --> 00:09:10.299
And on the Y axis, we have an evaluation score.

00:09:10.299 --> 00:09:15.940
So this is based on an evaluation of models specifically for sort of being the engine

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:17.859
of the chores package.

00:09:17.859 --> 00:09:23.979
And there are two important pieces for a model to be able to effectively carry out chores.

00:09:23.979 --> 00:09:28.340
One of them is that they respond very quickly.

00:09:28.340 --> 00:09:32.179
So kind of the current frontier of LLM research right now is reasoning.

00:09:32.179 --> 00:09:37.219
When models take two or five or 10 seconds to reason, you're just waiting in your IDE

00:09:37.219 --> 00:09:40.659
for something to happen, which is an unpleasant experience.

00:09:40.659 --> 00:09:46.340
But these sort of snappier, non-reasoning models tend to perform better.

00:09:46.340 --> 00:09:49.599
And then also, models need to be able to follow instructions really well.

00:09:49.599 --> 00:09:53.219
So I had that super long system prompt where I said, here's a bunch of examples of how

00:09:53.219 --> 00:09:55.020
you can carry out this task.

00:09:55.020 --> 00:09:56.700
Be terse, just do that.

00:09:56.700 --> 00:10:00.900
There are a lot of models, and especially like local LLAMA models right now, that will

00:10:00.900 --> 00:10:07.380
just like describe our lang to you inside of your source editor.

00:10:07.380 --> 00:10:09.659
OK.

00:10:09.659 --> 00:10:13.659
So we're looking at how well different models do on this eval.

00:10:13.659 --> 00:10:21.460
You can see in the top right, we have CloudSonic 4 coming in something like $1 per 100 refactorings.

00:10:21.460 --> 00:10:26.380
So especially compared to these more agentic processes that we're starting to see these

00:10:27.059 --> 00:10:31.419
models capable of, this is like pretty cheap in comparison.

00:10:31.419 --> 00:10:36.979
But cheap is relative to your perspective.

00:10:36.979 --> 00:10:41.340
In a sort of close second, Gemini 2.5 Pro is a thinking model.

00:10:41.340 --> 00:10:45.140
But it's actually pretty snappy, so it does well on this eval.

00:10:45.140 --> 00:10:49.260
And there's sort of a drop off from there in terms of price.

00:10:49.260 --> 00:10:52.159
There's two points here for Gemini 2.5 Flash.

00:10:52.159 --> 00:10:55.099
One of them is the thinking version.

00:10:55.859 --> 00:10:57.700
One of them is the non-thinking version.

00:10:57.700 --> 00:11:02.219
So the one that does better and is cheaper happens to be the non-thinking.

00:11:02.219 --> 00:11:05.940
That's just a chart crime.

00:11:05.940 --> 00:11:10.539
You might notice that there's no local LLAMA models on this chart.

00:11:10.539 --> 00:11:11.940
I'm doing my best.

00:11:11.940 --> 00:11:12.940
We're so close.

00:11:12.940 --> 00:11:13.940
We're almost there.

00:11:13.940 --> 00:11:16.020
I really wanted to be able to mic drop here.

00:11:16.020 --> 00:11:22.780
You don't need to put your credit card info down, but not quite there yet.

00:11:23.780 --> 00:11:30.979
Earlier this week, OpenAI dropped GPT-OSS, which is a model that I can run on this laptop.

00:11:30.979 --> 00:11:35.900
And actually, on the side of the evaluation in terms of correctness, like can you write

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:39.419
good Roxygen documentation, it nails it.

00:11:39.419 --> 00:11:42.260
But it takes like 30 seconds per response.

00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:48.020
So almost there.

00:11:48.020 --> 00:11:52.979
The other way to get around putting your credit card information down to try my R package

00:11:52.979 --> 00:11:58.380
is to use GitHub support, or GitHub as a provider.

00:11:58.380 --> 00:12:00.619
So they have a sort of generous free tour.

